        "author": {
          "name": "Olaf Weber",
          "email": "olaf@sgi.com",
          "date": "2016-06-16 10:27:46.000000000",
          "tz": 120
        },
        "committer": {
          "name": "Amir Shehata",
          "email": "amir.shehata@intel.com",
          "date": "2016-06-16 15:12:07.000000000",
          "tz": 0
        },
        "subject": "LU-7734 lnet: fix lnet_peer_table_cleanup_locked()",
        "message": "LU-7734 lnet: fix lnet_peer_table_cleanup_locked()\n\nIn lnet_peer_table_cleanup_locked() we delete the entire peer if the\nlnet_peer_ni for the primary NID of the peer is deleted. If the next\nlnet_peer_ni in the list belongs to the peer being deleted, then the\nnext pointer kept by list_for_each_entry_safe() ends up pointing at\nfreed memory.\n\nAdd a list_for_each_entry_from() loop to advance next to a peer_ni\nthat does not belong to the peer being deleted and will therefore\nremain present in the list.\n\nSigned-off-by: Olaf Weber <olaf@sgi.com>\nChange-Id: I92bf219dc93a79f7d90035ccfbb38cd251138c04\nReviewed-on: http://review.whamcloud.com/20824\nTested-by: Jenkins\nReviewed-by: Amir Shehata <amir.shehata@intel.com>\nTested-by: Amir Shehata <amir.shehata@intel.com>\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/multi-rail"
    }
  },
